\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa240\sb240\ql\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  However, what must be pointed out is that advances in the fields of AI come not just from technological improvement, but improvements of understanding of psychology, how natural systems work, and how to emulate natural processes (e.g. BOD). Also, a focus on technology smacks of utopianism and \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93technological fetishism\u8221\'94; the \u8220\'93prevalent idea\u8221\'94 in the industry that more complex = better characters, and that that complexity comes from technology or implementation. (}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf7\cb3\highlight3 egs of games recently that have touted complex AI?}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 ) The focus on \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93general-purpose AI\u8221\'94, or \u8220\'93strong AI\u8221\'94 (that bosses such as Insomniac guy from video think are coming, \u8220\'93respond to everything you say\u8221\'94) and the tweet about the misunderstanding amongst game bosses about the truth of the difficulty of AI. Look back at Herbert Simon\u8217\'92s overzealous predictions in 1957, and the fortunes of the AI industry. The quest for the \u8220\'93synthetic person\u8221\'94 - misunderstands what a character is. It must be partial. However, we have been making the wrong things partial. People expect too much from technology - expect fully fledged people. "it is difficult to create an artificial character that convinces a real person for more than a few minutes" - maybe we need to avoid this. This focus on believability - Really, then, this is resonance - believability is too limited a term. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Tence & Buche see \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91believability\u8217\'92 as \u8216\'91acting like a human\u8217\'92 - not always the case - I am not looking at their definition of \u8216\'91believability\u8217\'92, really. Generally, what we mean by believability is the consistency of the behaviors of the character, i.e. that the decisions the character takes are understood by the viewer. Believability, the way it is defined in this thesis, concerns itself with how natural the behavior of a character is, how far the actions of the character agree with what the player believes should happen in such a context. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is it (strong AI) necessary or even desirabele for practical benefits?\u8221\'94 Goodwinds. Newman - experience of playing games is kinaesthetic, not visual - about how it works as a system - autocosmics, rather than representational. How things sit in a systems.\u8221\'94This idea is in direct opposition to all current trends in animation, which take the route of desperately trying to look real, usually by realistic lighting and rendering, or by forcing a hand-made or naive appearance. At the time of writing, this trend shows no apparent signs of ceasing\u8221\'94 - too big a sphere. Prom Week - \u8220\'93social simulation game\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93make social interactions truly playable\u8221\'94. Emergent, systemic approaches to social situations just like in other games (use Angry Birds physics engine as example). \u8220\'935,000 rules of social norms and behaviours\u8221\'94 - not a sustainable way to do it. Role is now \u8220\'93aggressive machine learning (rather than hand-encoding of knowledge\u8221\'94 }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Game AI development is a mixture of techniques and infrastructure with aa generous dose of ad hoc solutions, heuristics and bits of code that look like hacks\u8221\'94 Learning - \u8220\'93hot topic\u8221\'94 in games. Has \u8220\'93the potential to produce more believable characters\u8221\'94}
