\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  Will technological advances have a ceiling? How far can we go? The end of Moore\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s law, processor density etc. We still have problems, especially with many technologies surrounding character-to-character interaction such as speech (Gris et al, Newell and Edwards 2008) - and when do we decide that we have \u8220\'93solved\u8221\'94 these problems? As Mullaney points out (drawing on the work of Lewis Jacobs), film became art when it moved past \u8220\'93scientific curiosity to a creative enterprise\u8221\'94 - focussing on subject matter, using the tools we have. Games are computational in their uniqueness. Their graphics are not what define them. How they computer is important. New technology has not made films better, has it? OK, it is a traditional narrative technique, but still\u8230\'85 NWF points out that realism does not give us more authorial control. While we no longer have a \u8220\'93quest for perfect illusion\u8221\'94 (Manovich), it is still talked about in how we build our characters. "The dominances of photographic and cinematic imagery", very \u8220\'93efficient for cultural }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 - but we have another way to communicate, a more challenged but particular way. Don\u8217\'92t want to abandon computationality. Bogost on simulators - \u8220\'93The closer one gets to the perfection of a simulacrum\u8230\'85 the more evident it becomes\u8221\'94. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Dansky (2007) - "immersion is arguably the ultimate goal of videoogames" - issues of identification }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 "fully simulate human though, behaviour, emotions is a long way off" - but this is missing the point entirely! Issue also that it is contained on a machine - the "naive physics of computing" - a book can do what a book can do, we don't expect it to do anything else - we feel that there is no upper bound to the machine. These ideas of realism and freedom in games do not correspond to drama - need more limitation (Re. Laurel). "graphic sophistication began yielding diminishing returns" - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Increasingly visceral representational technologies\u8221\'94. Not trying to make strong AI - we talk about it a lot, even if we do not rely on it in our games or art. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf6\cb3\highlight3 Vaucanson\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s duck - a \u8220\'93good example of simulation\u8221\'94 - not the innards, just the excretions. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A simulator will become a work that shows the intrinsic impossibility of representing a chosen subject with playable computer graphics, rather than computation\u8217\'92s inevitable mastery of the physical world\u8221\'94."the achievement of photorealism is the main goal of research in the field of computer graphics" - manovich sees this as the reason they aren't seen as art. Uncanny valley becomes a problem. }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_J._Russell"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf8\cb3\highlight3 Stuart Russell}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \~and\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Norvig"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf8\cb3\highlight3 Peter Norvig}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \~observe that most AI researchers "don't care about the strong AI hypothesis\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 as long as the program works, they don't care whether you call it a simulation of intelligence or real intelligence."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_room#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig2003947-4"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\super\cf8\cb3\highlight3 [}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\super\cf8\cb3\highlight3  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf6\cb3\highlight3 Think that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93serious technical limitations\u8221\'94 no longer exist - I think they do. Partiality - Anthropy and Clark talk about "elegance" of design keeping things as simple as possible.In theater, we write a script, but the actor\u8217\'92s performance of it is up to her. But we nevertheless compose the shape of the scene. We give the player (another theater word) liberty to perform a scene; this is where the choices come in. The choices that a player makes come from the verbs we give her, so we have the ability to constrain and design what those choices are. A fictionalized ideal of the videogame is that it gives the player the ability to do anything, to choose anything. There are games that aim for this kind of wish fulfillment and mostly result in weak}
