\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb3\highlight3 The \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91Indie Scene\u8217\'92 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 - Often seen as a saviour for the artform, indeed elevating to an \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91artform\u8217\'92 - many resonant characters come from these games (}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf7\cb3\highlight3 examples?}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 ). Developed between 2008/2010 (Indie Entitlement). Is it that different? \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93White dudes remaking Mario\u8221\'94 ( Anna Anthropy). Points out blurring of boundaries between mainstream and indie. Characters still have this problem here - more \u8216\'91serious\u8217\'92 subject matter, but still handled using existing paradigms, often. Important to resonant character, but not the \u8216\'91saviour\u8217\'92 as it is portrayed to be. A \u8216\'91stagnant culture\u8217\'92 with a \u8216\'91cult of marketability\u8217\'92. Still "simple technological 'hook'[s] or larger-scale complicated technical systems." \u8220\'93the indie space is little different from the AAA space" (Indie Entitlement). The rise of the \u8220\'93empathy game\u8221\'94, which systematise emotions, or just layer emotion over existing game designs. \u8216\'91Empathy is not a genre\u8217\'92. Or often constrain narrative (games without characters, games with restricted characters) or the system, which is fine, but not all games can do this.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3  "games have been ringing changes on the same few subjects". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 In indie games, even though the dressing is different, the mechanics underneath are often the same. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Much \~of \~the \~\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93indie \~games\u8221\'94 movement \~is \~about \~questioning \~the \~designed \~presumptions \~of \~mainstream commercial \~games. - is it really, Eric? }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 We can\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t always rely on puzzles, gamey elements for our characterisation. The home of the \u8220\'93reflective choice\u8221\'94, and indeed the \u8220\'93reflective\u8221\'94 NPC (TWD) - not really systemic. Nothing wrong with this, but not potential. \u8220\'93Your decision\u8230\'85 will be of ethical importance to yourself.\u8221\'94 The \u8216\'91illusion\u8217\'92 of choice, as well. \u8220\'93Illusion of control\u8221\'94 (klug) - maybe need to choose more carefully what is controlled. Tightly controlled realm in TWD and Fables, but still has issues. "This has lead to both creative and critical tensions over the past decade with the rise of genres that put aside an interest in intellectualised and complex systems in place of invoking particular emotions." }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb3\highlight3 These guys (Anthropy and Clark) are talking about 'games', which have a specific goal as a piece of art - not all computer systems need this. I\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92m more with Samyn. A lot of what she talks about is about moving in space, rules, manipulation, power, danger.  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "zinesters" - anna anthropy - Difficulty of changing the culture - " a world of roguelikes, in-jokes and assumed knowledge?". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93In recent years low-interaction, low-challeneg 3-D games have become quite popular\u8221\'94. T (rapture)Trying to frame NPC convos with camera - a type of agency. TWA (study) - felt that strong characterisation not tied to her interactions, didn\u8217\'92t lead to character development \u8220\'93doing the story for them\u8221\'94 - "empathy is not a genre" - not just the types of stoories, but the types of systems.}
