\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 The problems are large, and widespread, and make creating resonant computational characters very difficult. It is a problem that reflects on the challenges of narratives in computational art in general - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93repetitive themes and stereotyped storylines\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Ryan), beautiful but empty worlds, and a continuing lack of resonance despite great technological advances. Characters that we don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t \u8220\'93give a shit\u8221\'94 about (Life Is Strange lady at AI Summit), \u8220\'93too simple\u8221\'94 nodal, mechanical realities, subservient to the game\u8217\'92s structure, in which the \u8220\'93pretty fragile\u8230\'85 illusion of humanity\u8221\'94 (Elizabeth talk) is routinely destroyed, to the point where it is no longer worried about, and even lampooned and capitalised by the companies that produce such characters. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "The best interactive stories are still worse than even middling books and films". \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Hardly any games, or interactive media of any sort, can reasonably aspire to character believability within this technical generation.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Togelius) - still sees it as an issue of tech! }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "such game moments are far too rare" }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 - characters as drivers of emotions in games. Games are still about "mainly interacting with purely "physical" processes"  }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cb3\highlight3 Jesper Juul (more ludologist) - in zimmerman's piece in First Person - maybe privileging character, plot etc. is the problem, that games aren'y goof gor this. "asking games to focus on their weaknesses rather than their strengths"}
