\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Some people think we should give up. Ludologist/narratologist debate - games, and by extension computer systems, cannot do empathy, or character, very well, because of their }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 very nature}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 . Celia Pearce points out that games, producing unauthored experiences, will find characters outside of the avatar very difficult. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "Games are good at objectification. Stories are good at empathy. Games tend to quantise, reduce and classify. Stories tend to blur, deepen and make subtle distinctions"}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 . }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The objective of creating a fully believable NPC within a game may be an impossible one.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  Koster questions whether games can do things like character well. Literature is more broad in its outlook. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "Can a game designer pick anying to simulate, or are there inherent limitations" }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 - Robinett thinks that anything can be simulated. S+Z think that the fact that games need to be about conflict might predispose games to certain narratives. (Conflict over territory (char as enviro), economic conflict or conflict over knowledge.) but that there is the potential for exploration. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Just as in real life, the worlds of literary fiction are replete with complicated individuals whose inner lives are rarely easily discerned but warrant exploration.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf6\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Videogames tend to focus on fighting and strategy, exploration, puzzle-solving\u8230\'85 these types of external conflicts are far easier to portray in a game-like fashion than the more internal emotional conflicts that are often the focus of things like romance novels and sitcoms.\u8221\'94}
